# HTML Best Practices

- Use semantic elements (header, nav, main, article, section, aside, footer)
- Choose elements based on meaning, not appearance
- Use headings (h1-h6) in proper hierarchical order
- Use lists (ul, ol) for grouped content
- Always include alt attributes for images
- Use proper form labels and fieldsets
- Ensure sufficient color contrast
- Implement proper ARIA labels when needed
- Use semantic elements to convey meaning to screen readers
- Include proper DOCTYPE declaration
- Use valid HTML5 structure
- Include meta viewport tag for responsive design
- Set appropriate lang attribute on html element
- Use proper meta tags for SEO and social media
- Optimize images with appropriate formats and sizes
- Use preload for critical resources
- Implement lazy loading for images below the fold
- Minimize HTTP requests
- Use appropriate caching strategies
- Use appropriate input types (email, tel, date, etc.)
- Implement proper form validation
- Use fieldsets and legends for grouped form controls
- Provide clear error messages and feedback
- Ensure forms are keyboard accessible
- Use CSS Grid and Flexbox for layout instead of tables
- Implement proper responsive images with picture element
- Use web components when appropriate
- Leverage native HTML validation attributes
